choice of UUID4 was borderline arbitrary, any unique ID will be fine.

"Every release should always have a unique release ID, such as a
timestamp of the release (such as 2011-04-06-20:32:17) or an
incrementing number (such as v100). Releases are an append-only ledger
and a release cannot be mutated once it is created. Any change must
create a new release."

After patch it should work like this:

1) Suggestion created in OPAC - currency defaults to NULL in database

3) Creating a new suggestion in staff will default to active currency.

7146 (Update timestamps when deleting a biblio)

Currently, when you delete an item, the timestamp column in deleteditems is
updated with current time. (This comes from an [unintentional] additional
update statement in DelItem.) It makes deletion time visible.
In the past, the marcxml was updated too at that moment, resulting in an
updated timestamp in biblioitems too. The timestamp in biblio was not touched.

If you delete a biblio however, the timestamps in deletedbiblio and
deletedbiblioitems do not reflect time of deletion. They still show the time of
last update before the record was deleted. This last update can be extracted
from MARC field 005 too.

This behavior is not consistent nor logical. I would suggest to add a statement
in DelBiblio to force updating the timestamp in deletedbiblio(items) too. It
makes the time of deletion visible in the record too. The time of deletion of a
biblio can be very useful for e.g. synchronizing purposes.

issue.title: [postgres] tests failing
issue.body:
trying to get the tests for PR https://github.com/propelorm/Propel/pull/144 up and running i noticed that the tests for postgres are failing. its failing on windows7x64 with postgresql-x64-9.0 and on debian squeeze with postgres 8.4.9-0squeeze1
i also tested my old patch-1 branch and i tested the current propelorm/Propel master branch.

at the beginning i thought its a windows problem, but after testing it on linux i think its a general problem while using postgres as test database.

most of the errors are quotation errors like:

```
-'DELETE FROM `book` WHERE book.TITLE='War And Peace' AND book.ID=12'
+'DELETE FROM book WHERE book.TITLE='War And Peace' AND book.ID=12'
```

also postgres is much more strict than mysql, maybe it is a discussion point to switch to postgres for testing. if a test works with postgres it will work for mysql (for stuff like null values and so on).

```
1) GeneratedObjectRelTest::testSetterCollectionSavesForeignObjects
PropelException: Unable to execute INSERT statement [INSERT INTO book (ID, TITLE) VALUES (:p0, :p1)] [wrapped: SQLSTATE[23502]: Not null violation: 7 ERROR:  null value in column "isbn" violates not-null constraint]
```


for fixtures: namespaced and bookstore

build.properties 
```
propel.project = bookstore_namespaced
propel.database = pgsql
propel.database.url = pgsql:dbname=test
propel.disableIdentifierQuoting = true
propel.schema.autoPrefix = true
propel.database.user = test
propel.database.password = test
propel.targetPackage = bookstore
```

runtime-conf.xml

```
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="ISO-8859-1"?>
<config>
	<propel>
		<datasources default="bookstore_namespaced">
			<datasource id="bookstore_namespaced">
				<adapter>pgsql</adapter>
				<connection>
					<classname>DebugPDO</classname>
					<dsn>pgsql:dbname=test</dsn>
					<user>test</user>
					<password>test</password>
					<options>
						<option id="ATTR_PERSISTENT">false</option>
					</options>
					<attributes>
						<option id="ATTR_EMULATE_PREPARES">true</option>
					</attributes>
					<settings>
						<setting id="charset">utf8</setting>
					</settings>
				</connection>
			</datasource>
		</datasources>
	</propel>
</config>
```

used commands/config
```
aptitude install postgresql php5-cli php5-pgsql php5-sqlite3 php-pear php5-mysql
pear upgrade
pear channel-discover pear.phpunit.de
pear install -a -f phpunit/PHPUnit
pear channel-discover pear.phing.info
pear install -a -f phing/phing

su postgres
createuser --pwprompt --encrypted --echo test
createdb --owner=test --echo --encoding=UTF8 test

cd /path/to/propel/test 
bash ../generator/bin/propel-gen fixtures/bookstore main
bash ../generator/bin/propel-gen fixtures/bookstore insert-sql 

bash ../generator/bin/propel-gen fixtures/namespaced main
bash ../generator/bin/propel-gen fixtures/namespaced insert-sql 

/etc/postgresql/8.4/main/pg_hba.conf
local	test		test							trust

phpunit testsuite

I'm not 100% sure of the current state, but previously there was 2 (at least) problems with the Propel testsuite on PostgreSQL.

 1. Transactions. Propel testsuite runs in an isolated transaction (afaik). In a case of a failed SQL query, the transaction on PostgreSQL is marked as errorneous and any further query will fail as the transaction isn't actually rollbacked as per propels own "nested transactions" implementation.
 1. MySQL formatting. The ModelCriteria sql-tests assert against mysql syntax (like $this->assertEquals('SELECT * FROM `foo`', $sql); ) I don't know if this can be "fixed". We need to hard code to some SQL syntax.

What I have done, is to run the complete test suite on mysql and run just specific tests against PostgreSQL when dealing with PostgreSQL-specific stuff. The problem with this approach is that I can't run "regression tests", as I don't know what my patch has broken on PostgreSQL..

This is definitely something we could try address in Propel2, at least..

issue.title: Devise is ApplicationController-centric to a fault
issue.body:
It used to be that Rails programmers wrote their application as a single Rails program. These days, many of us are writing our applications as collections of multiple engines, with nothing in the central application except what is necessary to load those engines and mount their routes. Devise fails that sort of application in multiple ways. So many ways that it's probably time for the Devise documentation to bear a warning that it doesn't work at present to use Devise from engines.

Devise internals depend on `ApplicationController`, and Devise installs its methods and helpers in `ApplicationController`. Engine-centric applications are unlikely to contain an `ApplicationController`.

Instead of installing them in `ApplicationController`, use something like this to install Devise methods and helpers. This installs in both `ActionController::Base` *and* its descendants, as there will be some descendants that have been initialized before Devise:

```ruby
ActionController::Base.class_eval do
  # Install methods and helpers here.
end
ActionController::Base.descendants.each do |klass|
  klass.class_eval do
    # Install methods and helpers here.
  end
end
```

Devise expects its named routes to live in `main_app`. The only way to tell Devise that the named routes are in an engine's route table is to re-write all of its views by hand.

Devise expects a root URL handler in `main_app` rather than an engine, and can't fall back if there isn't one. Here's one way to fall back:

```ruby
main_app.respond_to?(:root_url) ? main_app.root_url : '/'
'''

When used from a namespaced engine, Devise points all of its routes to controllers in the engine rather than Devise. The only way to turn this off seems to be to define *all* of the controllers used by Devise, just defining :module is insufficient, the result doesn't match the internal controller paths in Devise.

comment.body:
Thanks for the detailed report. Some comments to the issues you raised:

1) About `ApplicationController` and `ActionController::Base`, we have two options. Provide a convenience method that installs helpers in any controller, so one can do:

```ruby
class Engine::ApplicationController
  Devise.install_helpers(self)
end
```

Or simply adding configuration to ActionController::Base. Adding to ActionController::Base has the side effect of polluting all controllers and, in any case, I don't think we should loop over the descendants. If an engine depends on Devise, it is its job to ensure Devise was loaded before it.

2) Rewriting the views is a necessary evil and it is fine imho. The views are supposed to be a stub (very similar to scaffold) and you need to touch them anyway.

3) root_url certainly needs to be fixed

4) namespace engine issue needs to be fixed as well

Will you be willing to send patches to solve those issues? I can provide any guidance you need. We want to release Devise 2.0 and I would love if we could make this release work better with Engines, even if we need to cut Rails 3.0 compatibility (only Rails 3.1 forward).

issue.body:
Marc,

I've been looking for a map generation app employing continental drift for years and was delighted to find that someone finally made one! I noticed that the user interface was one of the areas you had mentioned as an area for improvement, and I had some feedback I wanted to share with you after experimenting with it for a while now. User Interface:
I found myself wanting to repeatedly generate new maps to see what possibilities would emerge. However having to reopen the menu and retype a new seed each time quickly became tedious.

* Make the New Map dialog persistent as either a side panel or a floating toolbar
   - eliminates 2 clicks & 3 mouse movements
* Display the Random Seed that was used to create the current map in the New Map dialog
   - allows the user to keep hitting the button to generate a new map while being able to note a seed that produced results they like so they can revisit it later
* A checkbox to keep the currently displayed seed, or to randomize a new one
   - gives the user the ability to reset the current map
   - allows randomizing without having to clear the Random Seed box
* A checkbox to automatically increment the current Random Seed when the New Map button is pressed
   - works when the suggested keep Random Seed option is checked
   - the user could keep generating new maps in a methodical fashion

Happy New Year and hope to hear back from you. If you'd like to contact me, I can be reached at:

issue.body:
My apologies if this is a duplicate, but I can't seem to get ffmpeg to build on Mac OS X 10.6.8 with Xcode 4.2 (MacBook 1,1). Here's my brew doctor output:

    $ brew doctor
    We couldn't detect gcc 4.2.x. Some formulae require this compiler.
    NOTE: Versions of XCode newer than 4.2 don't include gcc 4.2.x.
    
    $

And here's the build log when using `--use-clang`: https://gist.github.com/1546620 . Naturally, it also fails with `--use-llvm`. Looking around, I can see this issue has been reported to LLVM and apparently fixed: http://llvm.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=6309

I've also heard that using gcc to compile ffmpeg 0.9 works, but since Xcode 4.2 doesn't ship with gcc, that kind of makes it more difficult.

issue.title: Look ma, no commandhandlers!
issue.body:
90% of commandhandlers only do the following:

1. Determine whether they are creating the aggregate root or not
2. Find the aggregate root (or create it)
3. Invoke a method on the aggregate root.

I think these can all be accomplished via attributes on the command. The following is a command handler, with an aggregate root of "User" and invokes a method of "ChangeAddress":

        [CommandHandler(AggregateRootAction.Update, typeof(User))]
